whose members, including some who were not of Filipina/o descent, chose to pursue options in the U.S. or in the Philippines.Fujita-Rony also shows how racism against Filipina/o Americans led to constant mobility into and out of Seattle, making it a center of a thriving ethnic community in which only some remained permanently, given its limited possibilities for employment. The book addresses class distinctions as well as gender relations, and also situates the growth of Filipina/o Seattle within the regional history of the American West, in addition to the larger arena of U.S.-Philippines relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFilipino AmericanszWashington (State)zSeattlexHistoryy20th century. 0aFilipino AmericanszWashington (State)zSeattlexSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aImmigrantszWashington (State)zSeattlexHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantszWashington (State)zSeattlexSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  aacademic.  aamerican history.  aasian american.  aasian communities.  aasian immigrants.  acolonial.  acolonialism.  acommunity.  aethnic groups.  afilipina.  afilipino.  agender studies.  aimmigrants.  aimmigration.  aminority communities.  aminority groups.  apacific northwest.  aphilippine.  apostwar.  arace issues.  arace.  aracism.  aregional.  ascholarly.  aseattle.  aunited states history.  aus history.  awestern united states.  aworld war 1.  aworld war 2.  awwi.  awwii.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023094140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092772840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520927728423Coveruhttps://www